C is a high-level, procedural programming language developed in 1972 by Dennis Ritchie. It is the foundation for many modern languages and operating systems (including Linux).

Every C program must have exactly one **`main()`** function, which serves as the entry point of the program. Execution begins here.

To display text on the screen, C provides the **`printf()`** function. However, to use `printf()`, you must first include the Standard Input/Output library header file at the top of your program: **`#include <stdio.h>`**.

A simple C program looks like this:
```c
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    printf("Hello, World!\n");
    return 0;
}
```
Every statement in a C program must end with a **semicolon (`;`)**.
